Let me trace through the logic:

```java
boolean anyOtherEndTag(Token t, HtmlTreeBuilder tb) {
    String name = t.asEndTag().normalName();
    ArrayList<Element> stack = tb.getStack();
    for (int pos = stack.size() -1; pos >= 0; pos--) {
        Element node = stack.get(pos);
        if (node.nodeName().equals(name)) {
            tb.generateImpliedEndTags(name);
            if (!name.equals(tb.currentElement().nodeName()))
                tb.error(this);
            tb.popStackToClose(name);
            break;
        } else {
            if (tb.isSpecial(node)) {
                tb.error(this);
                return false;
            }
        }
    }
    return true;
}
```

The bug is that when iterating from the top of the stack downward looking for a matching end tag, if we encounter a special element before finding the match, we return false. However, the correct behavior should be to call `generateImpliedEndTags` BEFORE checking each node to see if it's special.

According to HTML5 parsing rules, when processing an "any other end tag" in the "in body" insertion mode, we should generate implied end tags (excluding the tag name we're looking for) before checking if elements are special.

The issue is that `generateImpliedEndTags(name)` is only called AFTER we find a matching node, but it should be called BEFORE we start checking nodes for being special.

